Fixed the bug where DYM shows duplicate suggestions

Currently, the `NameError#to_s` method attempts to append a suggestion
each time a NoMethodError is raised, which results in showing
duplicate suggestions. This commit changes the `#to_s` method to look
at the 'cause' exception to figure out whether it should append a
suggestion or not.

This reverts commit e2f5b2437f967565e4830eab6077f73ae166e0a7.

This change was made to special-case the NoMethodError caused by the `File.raed` call. But with the change 0a1b761 we can now properly suggest the `#read` method and we no longer need this change. Add a warning for misspellings of "initialize"

e.g.:

    $ be irb -rdid_you_mean/extra_features
    001 > class User
    002?>   def iniitalize(name)
    003?>     @name = name
    004?>   end
    005?> end
    warning: iniitalize might be misspelled, perhaps you meant initialize
     => :iniitalize
    006 >

Why `distance <= 2`? Take a look at these papers:

 * Damerau, Fred J., "A technique for computer detection and correction
   of spelling errors," Communications of the A.C.M., vol. 7,
   pp. 171-176, March 1964.
 * Pollock, Joseph J. and Zamora, Antonio, "Automatic spelling
   correction in scientific and scholarly text," Communications of the
   A.C.M., vol. 27, no. 4, pp. 358-368, April 1984.
Re-organize code

Add an extra feature that shouldn't be used in production

This adds the ability to correct a mistyped instance variable name:

    require 'did_you_mean/extra_features'

    @number = 1
    @nubmer.zero?
    # => NoMethodError: undefined method `zero?' for nil:NilClass
    #
    #    Did you mean? @number
    #

This implementation uses TracePoint which is not stable yet (also see: https://bugs.ruby-lang.org/issues/11667), thus it should only be used in development. From this point, any feature that should only be used in development should go into `did_you_mean/extra_features/` dir.

Add a verbose formatter

This verbose formatter displays the name corrections wrapped with extra
spaces/lines.

Without it:

    $ be irb -rdid_you_mean
    head :001 > pust "hi!"
    NoMethodError: undefined method `pust' for main:Object
    Did you mean?  puts
            from (irb):1

With it:

    $ be irb -rdid_you_mean -rdid_you_mean/verbose_formatter
    head :001 > pust "hi!"
    NoMethodError: undefined method `pust' for main:Object

        Did you mean? puts

            from (irb):1

Suggest private methods when a private method is called with args

Ruby will always raise an NoMethodError when a method is called with args.

  raiae
  # => NameError: undefined local variable or method `raiae' for main:Object

  raiae NoMethodError
  # => NoMethodError: undefined method `raiae' for main:Object

In the second example, did_you_mean should suggest the raise method.

Since this change, it'll look for the correct method name from private methods as well as public methods so that it can cover mroe cases.
Update CHANGELOG [ci skip]

Make sure to always append suggestions to a new string object

  * Exception#to_s creates a new string object if a message is *not* provided

    error = ((raise NameError) rescue $!)
    error.to_s.object_id # => 16993800
    error.to_s.object_id # => 16982100

  * It also reuses the same string object if a message *is* provided

    msg = "error"
    msg.object_id # => 17177860

    error = ((raise NameError, msg) rescue $!)
    error.to_s.object_id # => 17177860
    error.to_s.object_id # => 17177860

In the second example, `Exception#to_s` will have a duplicate message if
it's called more than once since did_you_mean makes a disruptive change
to the error message.

Let's create a new string object every time `#to_s` is called so that it
won't duplicate the same message.

reflection to get a receiver object so that we can say goodbye to the
current Java extension that relies on JRuby internals.

Fix build for Ruby 1.9.3

Fix the wrong jaro-winkler algorithm

Given we have 'does_exist' and 'doesnt_exist', The jaro_winkler gem
returns 0.9666... while the original implementation[1] returns 0.9066...

From a user perspective, both of the right and wrong ones don't actually
meet the user satisfaction, but the right one is slightly better as
sometimes the result would be lower than the wrong one.

[1]: http://web.archive.org/web/20100227020019/http://www.census.gov/geo/msb/stand/strcmp.c

Make Jaro distance colculation slightly faster

  Calculating -------------------------------------
                before     3.278k i/100ms
                 after     4.117k i/100ms
  -------------------------------------------------
                before     32.884k (± 6.0%) i/s -    167.178k
                 after     41.728k (± 6.0%) i/s -    209.967k

  Comparison:
                 after:    41727.7 i/s
                before:    32884.0 i/s - 1.27x slower

Implement jaro-winkler distance

So it doesn't have to be dependant on jaro_winkler gem.

Tweak Jaro-winkler distance scoring

It turns out that Jaro-Winkler doesn't handle short inputs nicely. Let's
change threshould depending on the length of the input so it can be
smarter even when the input is less than 3 characters.

Start using Jaro-Winkler distance

Leveshtein distance is great, but sometimes it doesn't catch a name that
should be caught. For instance, when 'drag' is typed and the correct one
is 'drag_to', did_you_mean fails to find 'drag_to'.
With Jaro-Winkler distance, suggestions will be more accurate.

Introduce #searches interface for finders

Now #words and #target_word interfaces have gone and #searches is the
new one. #searches method should return a hash which includes one or
more pairs of a target name (string) and a list of names (array of objects
that respond to #to_s). e.g.:

  class TheFinder
    include DidYouMean::BaseFinder

    def searches
      {"nubmer" => %w(number character symbol)}
    end
  end

  TheFinder.new.suggestions # => ["number"]

This allows us to easily add more types of suggestions in one class:

  class MultipleTypeFinder
    include DidYouMean::BaseFinder

    def searches
      {
        "nubmer" => %w(number character symbol),
        "sybmol" => %w(number character symbol)
      }
    end
  end

  MultipleTypeFinder.new.suggestions # => ["number", "symbol"]

Correct if the ivar name is wrong

Now did_you_mean suggests the right ivar name when there's a typo in an ivar name.

    @user_id = 1
    @uesr_id.zero?
    # => NoMethodError: undefined method `zero?' for nil:NilClass
    #
    #     Did you mean? @user_id
    #
